rmk: Calls from a male Cuckoo that, over the course of several mornings, sang from the same hillside. During its broadcast period, it flew a few times - but only a matter of metres from a post to a rock (and then, later, back to the post). The clip records the bird moving. Because the recorder was nearer the post, the volume increases. Roughly in the middle of the clip, some 'choking gurgles' are recorded. These are at 0:28 (two calls) and, the clearer of the two examples, 0:33. Because I left the recorder and retreated, I did not see if the gurgles were made in flight or, as I think more likely, upon landing. Later recordings, made when it was definitely perched, also contain a few gurgling notes.

Based on frequency measurements, this would be assigned as subtelephonus according to the 2015 paper in online Journal of Ornithology entitled 'Geographic variation in the calls of Common Cuckoo: isolation by distance and divergence among subspecies’. The birds in south China were considered by Cheng (1987) to be 'fallax', but this ssp was subsumed within bakeri according to Erritzoe et al. (2012 - Cuckoos of the World, Helm). I don't know who did this nor why. However, the frequency measurements of the song of this bird do not match bakeri (based on the paper above).
